Lethbridge is a beautiful city
with tremendous community pride

But as a resident...

You might be one
of the most wasteful
people on the planet

YES, YOU

In 2015, Lethbridge produced 1150kg of waste per person each year
[Source: City of Lethbridge]

Alberta: 977 kg/yr per capita
[Data from 2012, Source: Stats Can]
Canada: 712 kg/yr per capita
[Data from 2012, Source: Stats Can]
World: 578 kg/yr per capita
[Data from 2009, Source: Conference Board Of Canada]

As long as large numbers of people have lived together,
we have struggled to deal with our waste

But it wasn't always like that

Historically, we were far better
at reusing materials
than we are today.

With fewer resources available,
we needed to be more resourceful
about what we threw away.

As human populations grew,
so did the amount of waste we produced

We now consume more than ever

because we produce more STUFF than ever.

Unfortunately,

our thinking on how to dispose of waste

couldn't keep up with the pace of manufacturing.

Our cities

became clogged

with garbage

From the Galt Archives:

From the Galt Archive:

As our waste continued to grow,

we created dumping grounds

People often tossed garbage
down the side of the coulees

Modern landfills are engineered to better protect the environment
from the garbage we throw away

But it can still linger
for thousands of years

Even with recycling, which helps combat the problem of mounting garbage,

it's still a struggle for us to put waste in the right place

This is very apparent in Lethbridge's landfill

In 2015 our residential waste consisted of:[1]

TRASH

RECYCLABLES

ORGANICS

27%

25%

48%

Many of the materials that we are
burying in our landfills are simply

TOO

GOOD

TO

WASTE

Future generations will wonder at our behaviour.

Surely Lethbridge is not as wasteful as
other Canadian cities,

right?

Actually, we produce more waste in Lethbridge than almost
anywhere else in the world

Living in Lethbridge, each household throws away an average of

10 pounds of waste

EVERY DAY[2]

We also waste at work...

... and in our free time

There are 96,000 of us in Lethbridge.

Imagine how our waste piles up.

All together, it's enough waste every year to:

Fill the water tower 90 times...

... cover the deck of the High Level Bridge 10 feet high...

... or fill Galt Gardens 15 feet deep

Not very pretty, is it?

We can do better to preserve our beautiful city.

Lethbridge must waste less.

In 2015, Lethbridge produced 1150kg of waste per person each year
[Source: City of Lethbridge]

We may not see the costs of filling up our landfill on our bill every month, but we do pay a lot to operate and continually expand our landfill. Eventually future generations will pay to repair the damage to our environment.

From the City of Lethbridge:

"The area currently permitted for landfill is approaching capacity. At current disposal rates it is estimated that there is between 12 and 15 years of capacity available. The City has additional land adjacent to the centre and will be seeking approval from Alberta Environment to expand the landfills permitted area (or footprint) as well as the maximum height for waste placement."
Read More

But what about businesses - dont they make most of the garbage?

Its true - altogether we produce about twice as much waste outside of our homes, at the places where we work, shop, go to school, play or are cared for, such as in hospital.
Dont forget - its us who work at those businesses too. Whether at home or at work, we must do whatever possible to prevent needless waste.
Business waste is an area that City Council is aggressively purusing towards waste reduction, with policies etc.
We need to be responsible for doing our part at home as well.

So what is the solution?

You already know the answer.

If we want to have less garbage, we need to:

Reduce

the number of
things we buy

Reuse

what we can

Recycle

wherever possible

Compost

organic material
(48% of our waste)

All of us must do our part to help Lethbridge waste less.

We're not asking you to do it all.

We're simply asking you to do your part and change
one thing that creates less waste for our landfill.
